\begin_layout Subsubsection
Repeated-index or Enstein's notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A widely used tool for mechanics and physicians is the use of the 
\emph on
Einstein's Summation Convention
\emph default

\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Einstein's summation convention
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Einstein's summation notation was named after the German-born theoretical
 physicist Albert Einstein and introduced in 1916.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to simplify the mathematical expression by removing the implicit sum signs
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\sum$
\end_inset

) over repeated roman indices (
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k,l,...$
\end_inset

).
 In the following mathematical monomial 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}b_{i}$
\end_inset

, the implicit sum sign has been removed, so that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{i}b_{i}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}b_{i}=a_{1}b_{1}+a_{2}b_{2}+...+a_{n}b_{n}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

therefore, the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 index is a so-called 
\emph on
mute index
\emph default

\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Index!Mute index
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In the following monomial 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{ij}b_{j}$
\end_inset

, the implicit sum sign has also been removed, so that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{ij}b_{j}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}A_{ij}b_{j}=A_{i1}b_{1}+A_{i2}b_{2}+...+A_{in}b_{n}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and this time, 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
talking index
\emph default

\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Index!Talking index
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is a mute index.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A mute (or dummy) index is an index that does not appear in a monomial after
 the summation is carried out (it can be arbitrarily changed of 
\emph on
name
\emph default
).
 A talking index is an index that is not repeated in the same monomial and
 is transmitted outside of it (it cannot be arbitrarily changed of 
\emph on
name
\emph default
).
 It's important to note that an index can only appear up to two times in
 a monomial, if not, the expression must contain an error.
 The following rules of this kind of notation are given here after:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sum over all repeated indices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increment all unique indices fully at least once, covering all combinations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Increment repeated indices first.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The number of talking indices indicates the order of the tensor result at
 the end of the operation.
\end_layout

