\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Kronecker Delta and the Levi-Cevita Epsilon entities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Kronecker delta entity 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is usually defined by the following expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{ij}=\left\{ \begin{array}{lll}
0 & \text{if} & i\neq j\\
1 & \text{if} & i=j
\end{array}\right.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Both indices 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 may take on any value in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

.
 Only for the three possible cases where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=j$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 non-zero.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{ij}=\left\{ \begin{array}{llll}
1 & \text{if} & i=j & \quad(\delta_{11}=\delta_{22}=\delta_{33}=1)\\
0 & \text{if} & i\neq j & \quad(\delta_{12}=\delta_{13}=\delta_{21}=\cdots=0)
\end{array}\right.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

One can note that the Kronecker delta entity is symmetric so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ij}=\delta_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
 It's also obvious that, following the Einstenâ€™s notation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{ii}=\delta_{11}+\delta_{22}+\delta_{33}=3
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Kronecker delta serves as a replacement operator in many mathematical
 expression, so that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{ij}u_{j}=u_{i};\qquad\delta_{ij}A_{jk}=A_{ik}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Levi-Cevita Epsilon symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon_{ijk}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
+1\quad & \text{if even permutation of }ijk\\
-1 & \text{if odd permutation of }ijk\\
0 & \text{elsewhere}
\end{array}\right.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{123}=\epsilon_{231}=\epsilon_{312}=+1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{321}=\epsilon_{213}=\epsilon_{132}=-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{ijk}=0$
\end_inset

 if there is a repeated index.
 The Levi-Cevita symbol is also named permutation or alternating symbol.
 Another way to express the permutation symbol is by means of its indices:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon_{ijk}=\frac{1}{2}\left(i-j\right)\left(j-k\right)\left(k-i\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

