\begin_layout Subsection
Second order tensors and above
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to identify the tensor order by the number of free indices in
 the tensor components.
 Here after we are going to consider second, third and fourth order tensors.The
 tensor order is given by the number of free indices in its components.
 The number of tensor components is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{n}$
\end_inset

 , where the base 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the maximum value in the index range (usually 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

), and the exponent 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of free indices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Second order tensors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Extending the previously defined concept of section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:First-order-tensor"

\end_inset

 and more specifically by equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Dyadic-product"

\end_inset

), one can then define the notion of a second order tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 that can be written as a unique linear combination of the 
\begin_inset Formula $9$
\end_inset

 dyads 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{e}_{i}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{j}\equiv\overrightarrow{e}_{i}\overrightarrow{e}_{j}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\A & =\overrightarrow{u}\otimes\overrightarrow{v}\nonumber \\
 & =\left(u_{i}\overrightarrow{e}_{i}\right)\otimes\left(v_{j}\overrightarrow{e}_{j}\right)\\
 & =u_{i}v_{j}\left(\overrightarrow{e}_{i}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{j}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =A_{ij}\left(\overrightarrow{e}_{i}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{j}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

so that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\A & =A_{11}\left(\overrightarrow{e}_{1}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{1}\right)+A_{12}\left(\overrightarrow{e}_{1}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{2}\right)+A_{13}\left(\overrightarrow{e}_{1}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{3}\right)\nonumber \\
 & +A_{21}\left(\overrightarrow{e}_{2}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{1}\right)+A_{22}\left(\overrightarrow{e}_{2}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{2}\right)+A_{23}\left(\overrightarrow{e}_{2}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{3}\right)\\
 & +A_{31}\left(\overrightarrow{e}_{3}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{1}\right)+A_{32}\left(\overrightarrow{e}_{3}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{2}\right)+A_{33}\left(\overrightarrow{e}_{3}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{3}\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, this could have been written in a more compact form as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\A & =A_{11}\overrightarrow{e}_{1}\overrightarrow{e}_{1}+A_{12}\overrightarrow{e}_{1}\overrightarrow{e}_{2}+A_{13}\overrightarrow{e}_{1}\overrightarrow{e}_{3}\nonumber \\
 & +A_{21}\overrightarrow{e}_{2}\overrightarrow{e}_{1}+A_{22}\overrightarrow{e}_{2}\overrightarrow{e}_{2}+A_{23}\overrightarrow{e}_{2}\overrightarrow{e}_{3}\\
 & +A_{31}\overrightarrow{e}_{3}\overrightarrow{e}_{1}+A_{32}\overrightarrow{e}_{3}\overrightarrow{e}_{2}+A_{33}\overrightarrow{e}_{3}\overrightarrow{e}_{3}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In matrix notation, the second order tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 can be defined by the following relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\A\right]=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
A_{11} & A_{12} & A_{13}\\
A_{21} & A_{22} & A_{23}\\
A_{31} & A_{32} & A_{33}
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In index notation, the following expression denotes the second order tensor
 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 as a physical entity:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\A=\sum_{i,j=1}^{3}A_{ij}\left(\overrightarrow{e}_{i}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{j}\right)=\sum_{i,j=1}^{3}A_{ij}\overrightarrow{e}_{i}\overrightarrow{e}_{j}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the component 
\begin_inset Formula $ij$
\end_inset

 of the tensor in the given basis 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\A\right]_{ij}=A_{ij}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also define the second order unit tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Id$
\end_inset

 (or identity tensor) with the following rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Id=\delta_{ij}\overrightarrow{e}_{i}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{j}=\overrightarrow{e}_{i}\otimes\overrightarrow{e}_{i}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

