\begin_layout Subsection
Voigt notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In finite element implementations, symmetric second order tensors are often
 written as column matrices.
 In fact, in a symmetric second order tensor, only 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 values are independent, instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 so that one can hope a 
\begin_inset Formula $33\%$
\end_inset

 reduction of the size of the computational object used to store the content
 of this tensor in a computer memory.
 The procedure to convert symmetric second order tensors to column matrices
 is called the Voigt rule
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This type of notation is named after the German physicist Woldemar Voigt.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 By the way, the Voigt rule may takes two distinct forms depending on the
 nature of the tensor, whether it's a kinetic tensor (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 a stress tensor) or a kinematic tensor (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 a strain tensor).
 The Voigt rule for a kinetic tensor such as the stress tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sig$
\end_inset

 is the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Sig\equiv\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\sigma_{11} & \sigma_{12} & \sigma_{13}\\
\sigma_{21} & \sigma_{22} & \sigma_{23}\\
\sigma_{31} & \sigma_{32} & \sigma_{33}
\end{array}\right]\rightarrow\Sig\equiv\left[\begin{array}{c}
\sigma_{1}\\
\sigma_{2}\\
\sigma_{3}\\
\sigma_{4}\\
\sigma_{5}\\
\sigma_{6}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\sigma_{11}\\
\sigma_{22}\\
\sigma_{33}\\
\sigma_{23}\\
\sigma_{13}\\
\sigma_{12}
\end{array}\right]
