\begin_layout Subsubsection
Single index contraction or dot product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dot product (
\begin_inset Formula $\boxempty\cdot\boxempty$
\end_inset

), also known as the single index contraction product of two tensors takes
 the following forms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can define the dot product of a second order tensor by a first order
 tensor, leading to a first order tensor, so that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overrightarrow{c}=\A\cdot\overrightarrow{b}\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad c_{i}=A_{ij}b_{j}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the index 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is a mute index (index contraction) and index 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is a talking index.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can define the dot product of a third order tensor by a first order tensor:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\C=\IiA\cdot\overrightarrow{b}\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad C_{ij}=A_{ijk}b_{k}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the index 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is a mute index (index contraction) and indexes 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are talking indexes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can define the dot product of two second order tensors:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\C=\A\cdot\B\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad C_{ij}=A_{ik}B_{kj}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the index 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is a mute index (index contraction) and indexes 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are talking indexes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be noted that 
\begin_inset Formula $\A\cdot\B\neq\B\cdot\A$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\A\cdot\A=\A^{2}$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\A\cdot\A\cdot\A=\A^{3}$
\end_inset

 and so on.
 Based on this definition of the dot product and similarly as done with
 matrices, one can define the notion of the transpose of a second order
 tensor by the following rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\A\right]=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
A_{11} & A_{12} & A_{13}\\
A_{21} & A_{22} & A_{23}\\
A_{31} & A_{32} & A_{33}
\end{array}\right]\qquad\Rightarrow\qquad\left[\A^{T}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
A_{11} & A_{21} & A_{31}\\
A_{12} & A_{22} & A_{32}\\
A_{13} & A_{23} & A_{33}
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

so that we can write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\A^{T}\right)^{T}=\A;\qquad\left(\A\cdot\B\right)^{T}=\B^{T}\cdot\A^{T};\qquad\left(\alpha\A+\beta\B\right)^{T}=\alpha\A^{T}+\beta\B^{T}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And the notion of the trace of a second order tensor that yields to a scalar
 by the following rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tr\A=A_{ii}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the following associated properties:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tr\left(\A^{T}\right)=\tr\A;\qquad\tr\left(\A+\B\right)=\tr\A+\tr\B
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tr\left(\alpha\A\right)=\alpha\tr\A;\qquad\tr\left(\A\cdot\B\right)=\tr\left(\B\cdot\A\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tensor trace is an invariant, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 it is independent of the coordinate system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Double index contraction or double (vertical) dot product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The double index contraction (
\begin_inset Formula $\boxempty:\boxempty$
\end_inset

), also known as the double vertical dot product
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The double horizontal dot product (
\begin_inset Formula $\boxempty\cdot\cdot\boxempty$
\end_inset

) can also be defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\A\cdot\cdot\B\Leftrightarrow c=A_{ij}B_{ji}$
\end_inset

.
 In general, 
\begin_inset Formula $\A:\B\neq\A\cdot\cdot\B$
\end_inset

 unless one of the two tensors 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\B$
\end_inset

 is symmetric.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of two tensors takes the following forms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can define the double index contraction of of two second order tensors:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c=\A:\B\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad c=A_{ij}B_{ij}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the indexes 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

 are mute indexes (double index contraction) and the result is a scalar
 (a zero order tensor).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can define the double index contraction of a third order tensor by a
 second order tensor:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overrightarrow{c}=\IiA:\B\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad c_{i}=A_{ijk}B_{jk}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the indexes 
\begin_inset Formula $j,k$
\end_inset

 are mute indexes and index 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is a talking index.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can define the double index contraction of a fourth order tensor by a
 second order tensor:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\C=\IIA:\B\qquad\Leftrightarrow\qquad C_{ij}=A_{ijkl}B_{kl}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the indexes 
\begin_inset Formula $k,l$
\end_inset

 are mute indexes and indexes 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are talking indexes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Indices contiguous to the double-dot (
\begin_inset Formula $:$
\end_inset

) operator get vertically repeated (contraction) and they disappear in the
 resulting tensor (
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 order reduction of the sum of orders).
 Some usefull properties of the double dot product are given here after:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\A:\B=\tr\left(\A^{T}\cdot\B\right)=\tr\left(\B^{T}\cdot\A\right)=\tr\left(\A\cdot\B\right)=\tr\left(\B\cdot\A^{T}\right)=\B:\A
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Id:\A=\tr\A=\A:\Id
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\A:\left(\B\cdot\C\right)=\left(\B^{T}\cdot\A\right):\C=\left(\A\cdot\C^{T}\right):\B
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\A:\left(\overrightarrow{u}\otimes\overrightarrow{v}\right)=\overrightarrow{u}\cdot\left(\A\cdot\overrightarrow{v}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\overrightarrow{u}\otimes\overrightarrow{v}\right):\left(\overrightarrow{w}\otimes\overrightarrow{x}\right)=\left(\overrightarrow{u}\cdot\overrightarrow{w}\right)\cdot\left(\overrightarrow{v}\cdot\overrightarrow{x}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Symmetry and antisymmetry of a second order tensor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A second-order tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 is symmetric, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ie
\end_layout

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\A\equiv\A^{sym}$
\end_inset

, if the tensor is equal to its transpose:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\A=\A^{T}\qquad\text{or}\qquad A_{ij}=A_{ji}\label{eq:transpose-2nd-order}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

From the above it is clear that a symmetric second-order tensor has 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 independent components, namely: 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{11},\,A_{22},\,A_{33},\,A_{12},\,A_{23},\,A_{13}$
\end_inset

 and according to equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:transpose-2nd-order"

\end_inset

) a symmetric tensor can be represented by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\A=\frac{1}{2}\left(\A+\A^{T}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We can also note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\A=\overrightarrow{a}\otimes\overrightarrow{a}$
\end_inset

 is a symmetric second-order tensor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A second-order tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 is antisymmetric, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ie
\end_layout

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\A\equiv\A^{skew}$
\end_inset

, if the tensor is equal to the inverse of its transpose:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\A=-\A^{T}\qquad\text{or}\qquad A_{ij}=-A_{ji}\label{eq:transpose-2nd-order-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

According to equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:transpose-2nd-order-1"

\end_inset

) an antisymmetric tensor can be represented by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\A=\frac{1}{2}\left(\A-\A^{T}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the previous definition, any arbitrary second-order tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 can be split additively into a symmetric and an antisymmetric part:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\A=\frac{1}{2}\left(\A+\A^{T}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\left(\A-\A^{T}\right)=\A^{sym}+\A^{skew}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Determinant and inverse of a second order tensor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The determinant of a second order tensor yields to a scalar and is defined
 by the following rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\det\A=\det\left[\A\right]=\det\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
A_{11} & A_{12} & A_{13}\\
A_{21} & A_{22} & A_{23}\\
A_{31} & A_{32} & A_{33}
\end{array}\right]=\epsilon_{ijk}A_{1i}A_{2j}A_{3k}=\frac{1}{6}\epsilon_{ijk}\epsilon_{pqr}A_{pi}A_{qj}A_{rk}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and one can note the following properties:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\det\left(\A\cdot\B\right)=\det\A\cdot\det\B;\qquad\det\A^{T}=\det\A;\qquad\det\left(\alpha\A\right)=\alpha^{3}\det\left(\A\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 is singular if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\A=0$
\end_inset

, and nonsingular if 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\A\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 is nonsingular, there exists a unique inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\A^{-1}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 which satisfies the reciprocal relation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\A\cdot\A^{-1}=\A^{-1}\cdot\A=\Id
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The following properties are associated to the inverse of a tensor:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\A\cdot\B\right)^{-1}=\B^{-1}\cdot\A^{-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\A^{-1}\right)^{-1}=\A
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\alpha\A\right)^{-1}=\frac{1}{\alpha}\A^{-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The following notation is often used to represent the inverse transpose:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\A^{-T}\equiv\left(\A^{-1}\right)^{T}\equiv\left(\A^{T}\right)^{-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Orthogonal tensors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Orthogonal tensors play an important role in continuum mechanics.
 A second-order tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Q$
\end_inset

 is said to be orthogonal when the transpose 
\begin_inset Formula $\Q^{T}$
\end_inset

 is equal to the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $\Q^{-1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ie
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Q^{T}=\Q^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, it follows that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Q\cdot\Q^{T}=\Q^{T}\cdot\Q=\Id
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The orthogonal tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\Q$
\end_inset

 is said to be a proper rotation tensor if 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\Q=+1$
\end_inset

 and an improper (or a reflection tensor) if 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\Q=-1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tensor components depend on the coordinate system, so, if the coordinate
 system is changed due to a rotation so do the tensor components.
 The tensor components between these coordinate systems are interrelated
 to each other by a component transformation law.
 Consider a Cartesian coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},\,x_{2},\,x_{3})$
\end_inset

 formed by the orthogonal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{e}_{1},\,\overrightarrow{e}_{2}\,\text{and}\,\overrightarrow{e}_{3}$
\end_inset

 .
 In this system, an arbitrary vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{v}$
\end_inset

 is represented by its components as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overrightarrow{v}=v_{i}\overrightarrow{e}_{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now consider a new coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1}^{'},\,x_{2}^{'},\,x_{3}^{'})$
\end_inset

 represented by the orthogonal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{e}_{1}^{'},\,\overrightarrow{e}_{2}^{'}\,\text{and}\,\overrightarrow{e}_{3}^{'}$
\end_inset

.
 In this new system, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{v}$
\end_inset

 is represented by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overrightarrow{v}=v_{i}^{'}\overrightarrow{e}_{i}^{'}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As mentioned before, a tensor is independent of the adopted system, so:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overrightarrow{v}=v_{i}\overrightarrow{e}_{i}=v_{i}^{'}\overrightarrow{e}_{i}^{'}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Therefore, there exists an orthogonal second order tensor so that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v_{i}^{'}=Q_{ij}v_{j}\qquad\text{with}\qquad Q_{ij}=\overrightarrow{e}_{j}\cdot\overrightarrow{e}_{i}^{'}=\overrightarrow{e}_{i}^{'}\cdot\overrightarrow{e}_{j}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a second order tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 the same coordinate transformation law of the components between systems
 can be written using the following expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{ij}^{'}=Q_{ik}A_{kl}Q_{jl}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And so on for high order tensors with a correspondence between of the number
 of orthogonal tensors 
\backslash
Q and the order of the tensor whose coordinates have to be transformed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Spherical part and deviatoric tensor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the additive decomposition of tensors defined earlier, one can define
 the following expression for a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\A=\A^{sph}+\A^{dev}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\A^{sph}=\frac{1}{3}\tr\left(\A\right)\Id
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 is the spherical part of the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 and: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dev\A=\A^{dev}=\A-\A^{sph}=\A-\frac{1}{3}\tr\left(\A\right)\Id
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 is known as the deviatoric tensor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Norms of tensors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The magnitude (module) of a tensor, also known as the Frobenius norm, is
 given here after.
 The norm of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{v}$
\end_inset

 is given by the following expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert \overrightarrow{v}\right\Vert =\sqrt{\overrightarrow{v}\cdot\overrightarrow{v}}=\sqrt{v_{i}v_{i}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The norm of a second order tensor is a defined by the following expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert \A\right\Vert =\sqrt{\A:\A}=\sqrt{A_{ij}A_{ij}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The norm of a third order tensor is defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert \IiA\right\Vert =\sqrt{\IiA:\cdot\IiA}=\sqrt{A_{ijk}A_{ijk}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And the norm of a fourth order tensor is defined by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert \IIA\right\Vert =\sqrt{\IIA::\IIA}=\sqrt{A_{ijkl}A_{ijkl}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Eigenvalues and eigenvectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Computation of eigenvalues and eigenvectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The scalar product between a second-order tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 and a vector (or unit vector) 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{n}$
\end_inset

 leads to a vector.
 In other words, projecting a second-order tensor onto a certain direction
 results in a vector that does not necessarily have the same direction as
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The aim of the eigenvalue and eigenvector problem is to find a direction
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{n}$
\end_inset

Ì‚ , in such a way that the resulting vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{a}=\A\cdot\overrightarrow{n}$
\end_inset

 coincides with it, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ie
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\A\cdot\overrightarrow{n}=\lambda\overrightarrow{n}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous equation can be rewritten if the following expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\A-\lambda\Id\right)\cdot\overrightarrow{n}=\overrightarrow{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

And the solution of this set of homogeneous equations apart from the nontrivial
 solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{n}=\overrightarrow{0}$
\end_inset

 is obtained from
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\det\left(\A-\lambda\Id\right)=0\label{eq:Eigenvalues-equation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

leading to the characteristic polynomial, which is shown by a cubic equation
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda^{3}-\lambda^{2}\invI{A}+\lambda\invII{A}-\invIII{A}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\invI{A}=\tr\left(\A\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\invII{A}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\left(\tr\A\right)^{2}-\tr\left(\A^{2}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\invIII{A}=\det\left(\A\right)$
\end_inset

 are the three invariants of the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{n}$
\end_inset

 is a so-called principal direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 (or eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

) and the scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is called the associated eigenvalue to the eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{n}$
\end_inset

.
 For a given second order tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 , one can determine the three eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1},\,\lambda_{2},\,\lambda_{3}$
\end_inset

 and the three eigenvectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{n}_{1},\,\overrightarrow{n}_{3},\,\overrightarrow{n}_{3}$
\end_inset

 constituting a new space denoted as the principal space.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

 is a symmetric tensor, the principal space is defined by an orthonormal
 basis and all eigenvalues are real numbers.
 If the three eigenvalues are different, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}\neq\lambda_{2}\neq\lambda_{3}$
\end_inset

, the three principal directions are unique.
 If two of them are equal, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
eg
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}=\lambda_{2}\neq\lambda_{3}$
\end_inset

, we can state that the principal direction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{n}_{3}$
\end_inset

, associated with the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{3}$
\end_inset

, is unique, and, any direction defined in the plane normal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{n}_{3}$
\end_inset

 is a principal direction, and orthogonality is the only constraint to determini
ng 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{n}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{n}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In the principal space, the components of the tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\A$
\end_inset

